      <h2>Controls and Modes</h2>

      <h3>Variable Speed Trigger and Forward/Reverse</h3>

      <p>Pull the variable speed trigger <strong>(3)</strong> to start. The further it is pressed, the faster the chuck spins. Releasing the trigger engages the electric brake and the chuck stops immediately.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Forward (clockwise):</strong> press the forward/reverse control button <strong>(4)</strong> in from the right side.</li>
        <li><strong>Reverse (counterclockwise):</strong> press the control button in from the left side.</li>
        <li><strong>Lock‑off:</strong> center the control button. The trigger will not actuate.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note">
        The first run after changing direction may produce an audible click on start‑up &mdash; this is normal. Always wait for the motor to fully stop before reversing.
      </div>

      <h3>Mode Selection Collar</h3>

      <p>Rotate the mode selection collar <strong>(5)</strong> until the desired symbol aligns with the arrow. The DCD806 has three mode types:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Mode</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Drill bit</td><td>Drilling</td><td>No clutch &mdash; will stall if overloaded</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1&ndash;14</td><td>Screwdriving</td><td>Higher number = greater torque before clutch slips</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hammer</td><td>Hammerdrilling</td><td>No clutch &mdash; use carbide masonry bits only</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="warning">
        In the drill or hammerdrill positions the clutch is bypassed. The drill can stall and cause a sudden twist if the bit binds. Grip the tool firmly and anticipate the stall.
      </div>

      <h3>Speed Selection</h3>

      <p>The two‑speed gearbox is changed with the speed selector <strong>(8)</strong> on top of the tool. <strong>Stop the tool completely before changing speeds.</strong></p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Speed 1 (high torque):</strong> slide the selector <em>forward</em>, toward the chuck. Use for screwdriving and large‑diameter holes.</li>
        <li><strong>Speed 2 (high speed):</strong> slide the selector <em>back</em>, away from the chuck. Use for fast drilling in wood and metal.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>If the tool will not change gears, confirm the selector is fully engaged in either the forward or back position.</p>

      <h2>Installing a Bit in the Keyless Chuck</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcd806/p04_figD.png" alt="Keyless chuck with sleeve being rotated and a drill bit being inserted into the jaws" />
        <figcaption>Fig. D &mdash; chuck sleeve (7) opens the jaws of the keyless chuck (6) to accept the bit</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Turn the tool off and remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Grasp the black chuck sleeve <strong>(7)</strong> with one hand and hold the body of the tool with the other.</li>
        <li>Rotate the sleeve counterclockwise far enough to accept the accessory.</li>
        <li>Insert the bit shank about 3/4&Prime; (19&nbsp;mm) into the chuck <strong>(6)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Rotate the sleeve clockwise to tighten. Continue tightening past the first audible clicks &mdash; the chuck has an automatic spindle lock so it can be tightened with one hand. Tighten as far as you can.</li>
        <li>To release: rotate the sleeve counterclockwise.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        Never tighten the chuck by gripping the front and pulsing the trigger &mdash; this damages the chuck mechanism and can cause injury. The keyless chuck is unlocked after the first counterclockwise click; running the tool while unlocked can throw the bit.
      </div>

      <h2>Proper Hand Position</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcd806/p04_figF.png" alt="Drill held with one hand on the main pistol grip and the other hand cupping the battery pack underneath" />
        <figcaption>Fig. F &mdash; one hand on the main handle (14), the other on the battery pack (1)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>Place one hand on the main handle <strong>(14)</strong> and the other on the battery pack <strong>(1)</strong>. This anticipates the sudden reaction torque if the bit binds.</p>

