      <h3>ANTI-ROTATION System</h3>

      <p>The DCD806 senses tool motion and shuts down if the bit binds and the body of the tool starts to rotate. The red LED indicators <strong>(18)</strong> illuminate when the system has tripped.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Indicator</th><th>Meaning</th><th>What to do</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Off</td><td>Tool is functioning normally</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Solid red</td><td>ANTI‑ROTATION engaged &mdash; tool has shut down</td><td>Support the tool, release the trigger, then squeeze again to resume normal operation</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Operating Procedures</h2>

      <h3>Before Drilling or Driving</h3>

      <ol>
        <li>Set the speed selector <strong>(8)</strong> for the application (speed 1 for torque, speed 2 for fast drilling).</li>
        <li>Install the appropriate bit in the chuck.</li>
        <li>Set the mode collar <strong>(5)</strong> to drill, hammerdrill, or the desired clutch number.</li>
        <li>Confirm the workpiece is clamped or otherwise anchored.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Screwdriving</h3>

      <ol>
        <li>Rotate the mode collar <strong>(5)</strong> to a clutch number (1&ndash;14). Higher numbers slip at higher torque.</li>
        <li>Pull the trigger and apply pressure in line with the bit until the fastener is seated to depth.</li>
      </ol>

      <ul>
        <li>Start with a low torque setting and step up &mdash; this avoids stripping fasteners or marring the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Make practice runs in scrap to find the right clutch position.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Drilling</h3>

      <ol>
        <li>Rotate the mode collar <strong>(5)</strong> to the drill bit symbol.</li>
        <li>Place the sharp drill bit in contact with the workpiece <em>before</em> pulling the trigger.</li>
        <li>Apply pressure straight along the bit until you reach the desired depth.</li>
        <li>Keep the motor running while withdrawing the bit to prevent jamming.</li>
      </ol>

      <ul>
        <li>For large holes (5/16&Prime;&ndash;1/2&Prime;) in steel, drill a pilot hole (5/32&Prime;&ndash;3/16&Prime;) first.</li>
        <li>For thin or splintery material, place a sacrificial back‑up block behind the workpiece.</li>
        <li>For masonry, switch to hammerdrill mode and use carbide‑tipped masonry bits.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="danger">
        If the drill stalls, <strong>release the trigger immediately</strong>, remove the bit from the work, and find the cause of the stall. Do <strong>not</strong> repeatedly pulse the trigger to free a stalled drill &mdash; this damages the motor.
      </div>

      <h3>Hammerdrilling</h3>

      <p>Use carbide‑tipped or masonry bits rated for percussion drilling only.</p>

      <ol>
        <li>Set the speed selector <strong>(8)</strong> and rotate the mode collar <strong>(5)</strong> to the hammer symbol.</li>
        <li>Pull the trigger and apply just enough pressure to keep the bit from bouncing or rising off the work.</li>
      </ol>

      <ul>
        <li>Excessive force slows drilling and overheats the bit.</li>
        <li>A smooth, even flow of dust or chips means the rate is correct.</li>
        <li>Drill straight &mdash; side pressure clogs the flutes and slows the cut.</li>
        <li>For deep holes, withdraw the bit periodically (with the tool still running) to clear debris.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Belt Hook and Bit Clip</h2>

      <p>The belt hook <strong>(11)</strong> and bit clip <strong>(13)</strong> can be mounted on either side of the tool with the supplied screw <strong>(12)</strong> to suit left‑ or right‑handed users. To swap sides, remove the screw, move the hook or clip, and tighten the screw securely.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        Use the belt hook only to hang the tool from a work belt. Do not use it to tether or secure the tool to a person or object during use, and do not suspend the tool overhead. Confirm the screw is tight before each carry.
      </div>

      <h2>Tool Connect Chip</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcd806/p05_fig.png" alt="Underside of the drill foot showing the protective cover (20) being removed with two retaining screws (19) to expose the Tool Connect chip pocket (21)" />
        <figcaption>Fig. H &mdash; Tool Connect&trade; Chip pocket and protective cover</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>The DCD806 ships ready for an optional Tool Connect&trade; Chip (sold separately) that pairs with the Tool Connect mobile app for inventory management.</p>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Remove the two retaining screws <strong>(19)</strong> holding the protective cover <strong>(20)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Lift off the cover and drop the Tool Connect&trade; Chip into the empty pocket <strong>(21)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Reinstall the cover flush with the housing and torque the screws snug.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always remove the battery pack before cleaning or any maintenance.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Blow out air vents weekly</strong> with clean, dry compressed air. Wear ANSI Z87.1 eye protection while doing this.</li>
        <li><strong>Wipe the housing</strong> with a cloth dampened in mild soapy water. Never use solvents or harsh chemicals &mdash; they degrade the plastic.</li>
        <li><strong>Never immerse</strong> any part of the tool in liquid.</li>
        <li><strong>Battery and charger</strong> are not user‑serviceable. Wipe externally with a cloth or non‑metallic brush only.</li>
        <li>For repairs, brush inspection, or any internal service, send the tool to a DeWALT factory or authorized service center. Always insist on identical replacement parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Storage</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>Store fully charged batteries out of the charger.</li>
        <li>Cool, dry location away from direct sun and from temperatures above 104&deg;F (40&deg;C) &mdash; metal sheds and uninsulated trailers are unsuitable.</li>
        <li>Never store the tool with the trigger taped or locked on.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Transportation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Do not store, carry, or transport the battery pack so that exposed terminals can contact metal objects (loose nails, screws, keys, coins, hand tools). Shorted terminals can ignite a fire. Li‑ion packs should not be placed in checked airline baggage and must be insulated against shorts in carry‑on baggage.
      </div>

      <p>For DeWALT FLEXVOLT&reg; packs, attach the shipping cap before transport. The cap converts the pack to three separate 20V batteries at the lower "Shipping" Wh rating printed on the label.</p>

